content.description:
Find the chimney to shuffle up through. Climb a move or two, then start the climb from a good ledge.

This crack's crux is towards the top and is mostly 4's at that section.
content.protection: BD: 0.5-4.0, bring extra 4's. Optional protection in a secondary crack on the left (BD:0.4-0.5)
content.location: 4 routes to the right of 'Fist Full of Dollars'

content.description: A left-facing off-fingers flake corner with some variety. Brave the sand, it's worth it.
content.location: Far right of the prow. Look for a long left-facing corner and a tips to OW crack in the face to the left.

content.description: The best route I did at Eastwood for sure. Double fingers splitters with a cool dihedral for stemming lead into a roof with fingers in the back of a flare. More fingers and off-fingers await above the roof until the rock gets a little white.
content.location: Right of the prow about 5 minutes. There is a left-facing big hands crack to the right.

content.description:
Chossy start pulling up on a loose feeling refrigerator block. Enter a broken crack system that is easy, but has interesting moves. The business starts when trying to pull into the offwidth section.

If you're trying to figure out how to climb offwidth, this a good one to try. T-Rex only has about 8ft of slabbed out offwidth and can easily be aided with a few #5's
content.location: The top of the approach trail spits you out infront of 'Fist Full of Dollars'. is seven-ish routes to the right.

content.description: A definite sandbag for the big-fingered at 10+. Make thin moves on sandy edges or tips locks into a flake that gradually widens to OW. Be careful with the rock in the flake and note it is cracked on the left side.
content.location: Left of the unnamed 5.10+ left-facing corner that is Kelley #1. Far right of the prow

content.description: A gorgeous route unfortunately marred by a cam-eating roof, suspect rock, and interesting anchors. Fistful of Dollars splits the shield at the prow of the mesa and is the most obvious line from the road. Start in fingers to off fingers with death blocks for your right foot (seriously, don't touch them). Pull a roof on wide hands (mid-to-big #3s) and somehow don't let your cams get pulled back into the roof by the rope. Continue up two body lengths of fists before 5s and 6s for a third of the route to the anchors (four bolts).
content.location: At the top of the approach on the always sunny prow

content.description:
About 25' of low 5th class choss climbing is required before placing your first piece (BD #4.0). Climb this portion delicately and be rewarded with some 50' of fun jamming to the anchors.

**Beta Alert**

Crux is pulling the slightly steeper terrain protecting the anchor. There is a jug in the crack using another crack system in the back.
content.protection: BD: 1.0-4.0, mostly 2's and 3's. Optional 0.5's to protect the secondary crack
content.location:
To the right of T-rex, which is another another chossy-start route. T-Rex leads into to a broken crack system and ending with an off width section.

Colorado Swan is to the right to T-Rex and climbs a chossy low 5th class ramp to a left facing corner. There is a secondary crack just to the left of the main crack. I believe you can use BD 0.4 and 0.5's (Don't quote me on the gear size) to protect the secondary crack if you want.
